SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS FIRST AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (Agreement) is entered into on February 14, 2025 (the Effective Date), by and among (i) Headwaters Wind Farm LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Headwaters), Riverstart Solar Park LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Riverstart), Riverstart Solar Park II LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Riverstart II), and Riverstart Solar Park III LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Riverstart III); (each of Riverstart, Riverstart II, Riverstart III and Headwaters is sometimes referred to herein individually as a Co-Owner and collectively as Co-Owners) and (ii) Headwaters, in its capacity as the initial operator of the Shared Facilities (the Operator). The Co-Owner and Operator are sometimes referred to collectively as the Parties and each, separately as a Party.
RECITALS
A. The Co-Owners and its Affiliates are developing and have developed alternative energy powered electric generating facilities located on real property in Randolph County, Indiana (each of which is referred to herein as a Facility and collectively as the Facilities), each with a nameplate capacity of approximately:
Headwaters Facility: 200 MW Riverstart Facility: 200 MW Riverstart II Facility: 125 MW Riverstart III Facility: 100 MW
B. Headwaters and Riverstart were parties to that certain Shared Facilities Agreement dated May 31, 2020 (the Original Agreement).
C. Headwaters and Riverstart entered into an Amendment to the Original Agreement effective December 21, 2021 (First Amendment).
D. The Co-Owners entered into an Amendment to the Original Agreement effective February 3, 2023 (Second Amendment).
E. The Co-Owners wish to own or will own undivided interests in certain real and personal property acquired or to be acquired for their respective Facilities and wish to further share the use and cost of certain electrical transmission, communications¸ structures and other facilities and associated real property rights, and to engage the Operator to operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the recitals, the premises, covenants and conditions contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which the Parties acknowledge, the Parties agree as follows:
ARTICLE I -- DEFINITIONS, INTERPRETATIONS AND EXHIBITS 2 Docusign Envelope ID: 38746891-48D0-468A-B143-A9455D7886AC
1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Exhibit A.
1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Persons successors and assigns but, in the case of a Party, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Law means such Law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) hereunder, hereof, hereto and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) including means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, from means from and including, to means to be excluding and through means through and including.
1.3 Incorporation of Recitals and Exhibits. The Recitals set forth in this Agreement and the Exhibits attached hereto are incorporated into this Agreement by reference for all purposes.
ARTICLE II -- TERM OF AGREEMENT
2.1 Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the Effective Date and shall remain in force and effect until the earlier of (a) the date that is sixty (60) years after the Effective Date, and (b) the retirement and final disposition of all components of the Shared Facilities.
2.2 Payments on Termination. Upon termination of this Agreement, each Co-Owner shall pay Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest at the time of such termination as set forth herein this Agreement, of any remaining balance owed for Operators costs incurred or irrevocably committed to be incurred pursuant to this Agreement as of the date of termination, within sixty (60) days following receipt of an invoice from Operator requiring such payment; provided that Operator shall use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize such costs.
2.3 Survival. Any obligations of a Party to any other Party, including payment obligations and indemnity obligations, as a result of this Agreement which accrued prior to or as a result of termination of this Agreement shall survive termination of this Agreement.
ARTICLE III -- SHARED FACILITIES AND REAL PROPERTY

3.1 Shared Facilities. The Co-Owners plan to procure, install and construct, or have procured, installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, communications¸ structures and other facilities, as described in Exhibit B, which may be altered or reconstructed by amendment in accordance with this Agreement, for shared use by the Co-Owners (collectively, the Shared Facilities). Each grouping of Shared Facilities is described in Exhibit B (each a Shared Facilities Group). For the avoidance of doubt, the Parties hereby agree and acknowledge that the Headwaters Solely Owned Property, the Riverstart Solely Owned Property, the Riverstart II Solely Owned Property and the Riverstart III Solely Owned Property shall not constitute Shared Facilities.
3.2 Shared Real Property. The Shared Facilities in each Shared Facilities Group are or will be located on certain real property (collectively, the Shared Real Property) that is subject to the easement, lease, option or other rights and obligations in the documents described under the applicable section of Exhibit B (collectively, the Shared Real Property Agreements).
3.3 Shared Assets Groups. Each Shared Facilities Group, combined with the Shared Real Property corresponding to the Shared Facilities in such Shared Facilities Group (Shared Assets) described under the same section in Exhibit B shall be referred to herein as a Shared Assets Group.
3.4 Access. Each Co-Owner shall have a non-exclusive right of access (a) to the Shared Facilities in which it has an Undivided Use Interest as necessary in order to ensure that Operator is meeting its obligations with respect to operation, maintenance and repair of such Shared Facilities, that Co-Owners Facility remains operational, and for the purposes contemplated in Article VII; and (b) over any Shared Real Property in which such Co-Owner has an Ownership Interest; provided that, subject to the provisions of Section 13.1.4, if such Co- Owner is not the Operator, it shall (i) provide reasonable notice to Operator, and (ii) not unreasonably interfere with Operators operation, maintenance or repair of the Shared Facilities or of another Co-Owners Facility.
ARTICLE IV -- OWNERSHIP OF AND RIGHT TO USE SHARED ASSETS
4.1 Undivided Ownership Interests. Subject to Section 4.2.3 below, each Co-Owner owns or shall own an undivided interest, as a tenant-in-common, in the applicable Shared Assets Group (and equal to its Proportionate Share as set forth and described in Exhibit B in such applicable Shared Assets Group (such undivided interest of each Co-Owner being referred to in this Agreement as its Ownership Interest).
4.2 Undivided Use Interests. Each Co-Owner who has an Ownership Interest in a Shared Asset Group shall have an undivided right to the use or capacity of the applicable Shared Assets equal to its Proportionate Share therein, which right is exercisable on or after the date that all conditions precedent set forth in Section 4.2.3 below applicable to such Co-Owner (if any), are satisfied (the CP Satisfaction Date), by such Co-Owner providing written notice to the Operator and to the other Co-Owners in the same Shared Assets Group that the CP Satisfaction Date has occurred and providing an executed Bill of Sale and a Special Warranty Deed as set
4 Docusign Envelope ID: 38746891-48D0-468A-B143-A9455D7886AC
forth in Section 4.3 below (once exercised, such undivided use interest of a Co-Owner is referred to in this Agreement as its Undivided Use Interest), provided that such Co-Owner has made the payment or payments set forth in Section 4.3 and that no Event of Default has occurred and is continuing with respect to such Co-Owner. Each Co-Owners Proportionate Share in its Shared Assets Group is set forth on Exhibit C which may be revised from time to time in accordance with this Agreement.
4.2.1 Transmission Line. Each Co-Owner of a Transmission Line shall be entitled to use its Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line. In the event that the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line exceeds the capability provided in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, with Transmission Owners and Transmission Providers consent and approval, each Co-Owners Undivided Use Interest will be increased pro rata in accordance with its Ownership Interest for so long as the Delivery Capability is in excess of the capability provided in the Interconnection Agreements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Co- Owners will not exceed the Maximum Facility Output, as defined in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, unless all necessary approvals and consents are obtained (including from Transmission Owner and Transmission Provider).
4.2.2 Excess Capability. No Co-Owner shall have the right to use more than its Proportionate Share of the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line or portion of the Transmission Line. During periods in which a Co-Owner is not utilizing its full Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line or portion of Transmission Line, the other Co-Owner may utilize more than its full Undivided Use Interest, subject to the operating limits of the Shared Facilities, so long as such usage does not interfere with or adversely affect the first Co-Owners energy schedules and deliveries; and provided that (i) prior to any Co-Owner using more than its Proportionate Share of the Delivery Capability of the Transmission Line or portion of the Transmission Line, the Co-Owners shall have obtained all necessary approvals from Governmental Authorities, including Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acceptance for filing of an effective transmission services agreement for such usage to the extent required and (ii) no payment obligation will attach to such utilization by a Co-Owner of more than its full Undivided Use Interest.
4.2.3 Condition Precedent. The condition precedent to the CP Satisfaction Date for the Riverstart Project or any subsequent Additional Phase, as applicable, shall be a date that is sixty (60) calendar days after the Riverstart Project or such subsequent Additional Phase, as applicable, is granted both (i) a final order from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, as amended, authorizing the sale at wholesale of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services at market based rates, accepting a tariff providing for such sales and granting such waivers and blanket authorizations as are customarily granted by FERC and (ii) a final order from the Indiana Utility Regulatory Commission approving the transfer of Riverstart or the Additional Phase Proportionate Share of the Shared Assets. For the avoidance of doubt, there shall be no condition precedent to the CP Satisfaction Date with respect to Headwaters.
4.3 Reimbursement of Capital Costs. To compensate any Co-Owner (each, a Reimbursee), in each respective Shared Assets Group for having borne a disproportionate share of the costs and expenses of design, procurement, construction, installation and/or startup 5 Docusign Envelope ID: 38746891-48D0-468A-B143-A9455D7886AC
of the applicable Shared Assets in the respective Shared Assets Group, the Reimbursee shall be reimbursed by the other applicable Co- Owners in such Shared Asset Group (each, a Reimbursor), for such costs based on the estimate depreciated book-value agreed upon by the applicable Co-Owners in accordance with their respective Ownership Interests, as of the CP Satisfaction Date of the Reimbursor (including any Additional Phase). In connection with such reimbursement, the Reimbursee shall execute a Bill of Sale and a Special Warranty Deed for the benefit of each Reimbursor in accordance with their respective Ownership Interests substantially in the forms set forth herein as Exhibit F and Exhibit G, respectively.
4.4 Additional Phases. Subject to the consent of each other Co-Owner, a Co-Owner or its Affiliate shall have the right to build and operate an additional phase or phases (an Additional Phase), to connect such Additional Phase (or such portion of the Additional Phase as may be compatible with Transmission Owners interconnection facilities), to the Shared Facilities and to use the Shared Assets, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. Following the consent of the applicable Co-Owners to the applicable Additional Phase, the owner of such Additional Phase shall execute a joinder, the form of which is attached as Exhibit E hereto (the Joinder), and the Co-Owners shall execute an appropriate amendment to this Agreement to reflect the Undivided Use Interest of the Additional Phase in the applicable Shared Assets Groups. In addition, and in connection with the amendment, the Co-Owner of the Additional Phase shall reimburse any applicable Reimbursee as set forth in Section 4.3 above. Notwithstanding anything contained herein to the contrary, the owner of the Additional Phase shall bear any incremental costs and expenses of modifying and upgrading the applicable existing Shared Facilities to accommodate the connection of its Facility.
4.5 Initial Connection to Shared Facilities.
4.5.1 In connection with the initial interconnection of any Facility (a Connecting Facility) to any of the Shared Facilities, the Co-Owner that owns such Connecting Facility (the Connecting Co-Owner) shall be responsible for (and for all initial costs in respect of), the initial interconnection of such Connecting Facility to the Shared Facilities (the New Connection). Each Connecting Co-Owner acknowledges and agrees that the New Connection may result in (a) damage to the Shared Facilities or any other Co-Owners Facility; (b) claims from third parties and (c) lost revenues associated with scheduled and/or unscheduled outages and/or curtailment of some or all of the energy production from the New Connection of the Connecting Facility to any other Co-Owners Facility (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits, grossed-up based on the actual federal income tax rate applicable to the applicable Co-Owner, penalties imposed on the applicable Co-Owner or damages payable by the applicable Co-Owner to a power purchaser, energy hedge provider or transmission service provider for the applicable Co-Owners Facility) (together with related costs and/or expenses, collectively, New Connection Losses).
4.5.2 All New Connection Losses shall be the sole responsibility of the Connecting Co- Owner that owns the applicable Connecting Facility. As part of the process for implementation of any New Connection, the applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall establish a protocol to reasonably minimize disruptions to the Shared Facilities and any other Co-Owners

Facility. Within ten (10) Business Days after receipt of written notice from the applicable Connecting Co- Owner that the applicable New Connection has been completed, each of the other Co-Owners shall reasonably determine its actual New Connection Losses and deliver reasonable backup documentation supporting the calculation thereof to the applicable the Connecting Co- Owner. Any dispute regarding the calculation of New Connection Losses shall be determined in accordance with the dispute resolution provisions in Exhibit D. The applicable Connecting Co- Owner shall pay to each other Co-Owner all undisputed New Connection Losses incurred by such Co-Owner within thirty (30) days following receipt of the calculation of New Connection Losses from such Co-Owner. Any disputed New Connection Losses incurred by any Co-Owner that are determined (in accordance with the dispute resolution provisions in Exhibit D), to be owed by the applicable Connecting Co-Owner shall be payable by such Connecting Co-Owner to such other Co-Owner within thirty (30) days following such determination. Each Co-Owner shall have all other rights and remedies as may be provided in this Agreement or otherwise available at law or in equity resulting from any Connecting Co-Owners failure to pay any New Connection Losses.
ARTICLE V -- METERING, MEASUREMENT OF ENERGY DELIVERIES AND LOSSES
5.1 Measurement of Energy and Allocation of Losses. Energy transmitted on the applicable Transmission Line shall be measured and allocated between the Co-Owners of the Shared Facilities as set forth on Attachment B-2 to Exhibit B. The Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Revenue Metering Diagram depicts and delineates several metering connections used to measure energy and allocate losses by and among the Facilities, and such metering calculations are used to determine the Facilities generated real power delivered to and received from the point of interconnect.
5.2 Testing and Repair of Co-Owners Meters.
5.2.1 Inspection and Testing. If applicable and in conformance with the applicable Interconnection Agreement(s), a Co-Owner will cause meters (other than revenue meters owned by the interconnection provider and check meters owned by the individual Co- Owner) to be inspected and tested upon its installation and at least once every twenty four (24) months thereafter and at any other reasonable time upon the other Co-Owners request, which may not be made more than three times in said twenty four (24) month period. The Co-Owner requesting such inspection and testing will pay the costs of same, unless the results of the test show the Co-Owners meter to be inaccurate by more than half of one percent (0.5%), in which case the Co- Owners will share the costs of the test. Each Co-Owner will give the other Co- Owners reasonable advance notice of tests of its meter and the other Co-Owners have the right to witness such tests.
5.2.2 Calibration or Repair. If a test shows a Co-Owners meter to be inaccurate, the owner or owners of the meter will use reasonable efforts to cause its meter to be calibrated, repaired or replaced.
5.3 Back-Feed Power. The Co-Owners will arrange for the provision of back-feed power service for each of their Facilities.

ARTICLE VI -- OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES.
6.1 Engagement of Operator; Change of Control.
(a) The Co-Owners hereby engage the Operator to manage, operate, maintain and repair the Shared Facilities and to perform other duties pertaining to the Shared Assets (the O&M Services), all as set forth in this Agreement. The Operator accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof. Co-Owners acknowledge and agree that EDP Renewables North America LLC provides certain services with respect to the NERC Reliability Standards on their behalf and is the registered entity.
(b) In the event that there is a Change of Control of the Operator, the Operator hereby covenants and agrees to assign all of its rights, duties and obligations as Operator hereunder to the other Co-Owner and such other Co-Owner shall thereafter become the Operator. The Co- Owners shall cooperate with each other in effecting such transition and provide all notices to third parties and take all other actions deemed necessary or advisable by any of them with respect to such change in status. Effective as of the date of the assignment of the duties and obligations of Operator to the other Co-Owner pursuant to this Section 6.1(b), such Co-Owner shall assume responsibility for all obligations of the Operator thereafter accruing under this Agreement and the former Operator shall assume all obligations of a Co-Owner thereafter accruing under this Agreement.
6.2 Standards for Operators Performance. Operator shall perform or cause to performed the O&M Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the Material Project Agreements, the Shared Real Property Agreements, this Agreement and all Applicable Laws and requirements of Governmental Authorities, including without limitation all Hazardous Materials Laws and all Environmental Laws, and all safety policies and procedures (collectively, the Performance Standard).
6.3 O&M Services. The Operator shall provide or cause to be provided the following services on behalf of each of the Co-Owners who have an Undivided Use Interest from and after the date such Co-Owner has notified Operator of its exercised right to an Undivided Use Interest in the Shared Assets pursuant to Section 4.2 (the O&M Services Commencement Date):
(a) manage, supervise, operate, repair and maintain the Shared Assets, including the day to day management of the Shared Assets in accordance with Material Project Agreements¸ Good Utility Practice and the Annual O&M Budget; (b) pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Assets including but not limited to taxes and assessments pursuant to Section 12.2, and maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Operator in connection with its duties herein shall be maintained;
(c) expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities;

(d) notify every Co-Owner of any notice (or any other information reasonably anticipated to affect the Co-Owners) received by the Operator or received from any Co-Owner;
(e) manage compliance with the Co-Owners rights in Shared Real Property in accordance with the Shared Real Property Agreements, including making payments required thereunder; provided that the Operator shall have no right to amend such rights in the Shared Real Property; and
(f) with respect to the Shared Real Property and the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Real Property, oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the use, operation or ownership of the Shared Real Property or the Shared Facilities locate on the Shared Real Property.
6.4 Scheduled Maintenance. Operator shall schedule, or cause to be scheduled, maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities so as to minimize interference with Co-Owners scheduled energy deliveries. Maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities shall be scheduled, to the maximum extent possible, during scheduled maintenance outages of the Co-Owners Facilities. Each Co-Owner will provide to the Operator and the other affected Co-Owners by January 1 of each year a schedule of planned maintenance outages on such Co-Owners Facility for the subsequent twelve- month period. Scheduled outages of the Shared Facilities will be subject to the mutual approval by the affected Co-Owners, such approval not to be unreasonably withheld. Operator will seek to limit the duration of any outage, planned or unplanned, consistent with Good Utility Practice.
6.5 Unplanned Outages. Operator will notify, or cause to be notified, Co-Owners of all emergency or unplanned outages of any of the Shared Facilities as soon as practicable, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, and will provide an estimated time of return of the Shared Facilities to service, or if not known, will keep, or cause to be kept, Co-Owners advised regarding the status of same.
6.6 Emergency Conditions. In the event of an Emergency Condition involving the Shared Assets that could be reasonably expected by Operator to result in possible personal injury, loss of life, damage to or destruction of property, or danger to the public, the Operator shall, without the need for prior notification of the Co-Owners, take such action, or cause such action, as may be reasonable and necessary, as determined in the sole discretion of the Operator, to prevent, avoid or mitigate such loss, and shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, report any such emergency, including the Operators response thereto, to the Co-Owners, and Operator, if allowed by law, be compensated by the Co-Ownersfor the costs of taking such actions in proportion to their Ownership Interest in the Shared Assets so affected.
6.7 O&M Costs. Costs of performing O&M Services (the O&M Costs) shall be budgeted accordingly and include all payments made and expenses incurred by Operator in performing O&M Services (at cost and without markup), including but not limited to related overheads and applicable taxes, and costs (except insurance costs) related to ownership of the

Shared Assets.
6.8 Budgeting Process. Each year during the term of this Agreement, Operator will prepare a forecast budget of O&M Costs for the following calendar year and will provide a copy to Co-Owners by December 1st. Co-Owners will have ten (10) days thereafter to review the forecast budget and discuss any concerns with the forecast budget with Operator, provided that following the 10-day period such forecast budget of O&M Costs shall be deemed approved if no concerns are identified in writing by the Co-Owners. Operators implementation of the O&M Services consistent with the forecast budget is subject to Co-Owners prior approval, not to be unreasonably withheld (such approved forecast budget, the Annual O&M Budget)
6.9 Extraordinary Maintenance. Each Co-Owner agrees to reimburse Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of the costs of any maintenance or other services required in the event of unusual or catastrophic circumstances, to the extent such costs were not included in the forecast budget for O&M Services and incurred by the Operator (Extraordinary Maintenance), provided, however, the Parties hereby agree and acknowledge that Riverstart, Riverstart II, and Riverstart III shall be jointly and severally responsible (provided, that any such Co-Owner may seek reimbursement for any such liability from any such other Co-Owner that is also jointly and severally liable for such liability (A) in accordance with each such Co-Owners Facilitys installed nameplate capacity relative to the aggregate installed nameplate capacity of all such Co-Owners Facilities or (B) as otherwise determined pursuant to Section 6.10(c)) for ONE HUNDRED PERCENT (100%) of the Extraordinary Maintenance for the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Extra High Voltage Equipment, the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Control House Equipment, and the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Substation Equipment.
6.10 Responsibility for O&M Costs.
(a) Each Co-Owner shall be responsible for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of O&M Costs, including its share of the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance incurred by Operator, which shall be invoiced by Operator on a quarterly basis, provided, however, the Parties hereby agree and acknowledge that Riverstart, Riverstart II, and Riverstart III shall be jointly and severally responsible (provided, that any such Co-Owner may seek reimbursement for any such liability from any such other Co-Owner that is also jointly and severally liable for such liability (A) in accordance with each such Co-Owners Facilitys installed nameplate capacity relative to the aggregate installed nameplate capacity of all such Co- Owners Facilities or (B) as otherwise determined pursuant to Section 6.10(c)) for ONE HUNDRED PERCENT (100%) of the O&M Costs (in addition to any Extraordinary Maintenance as set forth in Section 6.9 above) for the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Extra High Voltage Equipment, the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Control House Equipment, and the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Substation Equipment. On or before the tenth (10th) day following the end of each calendar quarter, Operator shall invoice Co-Owners for their respective Undivided Use Interest of 1/4 of the amount of the current Annual O&M Budget, along with the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance performed in the previous quarter. The invoices shall be delivered to the parties identified in Section 17.15. Co-Owners shall pay such invoice within thirty (30) days of its receipt

(the Due Date). Any amounts not paid by the Due Date shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the then-effective prime rate of interest published under Money Rates by The Wall Street Journal, plus two percent per annum from the Due Date to the date of payment (the Late Payment Rate). For purposes of this Section 6.10 and for Section 6.11, receipt shall mean the date upon which the invoice is received in accordance with Section 17.15. In the event that any Due Date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such payment shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter. (b) Within sixty (60) days after the end of each calendar year, Operator shall invoice the Co- Owners for, or shall refund to the Co-Owners, as applicable, their Proportionate Shares of the difference between the sum of the Annual O&M Budget and the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance and the actual amount of O&M Costs paid or incurred in such calendar year. Any invoice for such amounts shall be paid within the Due Date. The invoices shall be delivered to Co-Owners as set forth in Section 17.15. Any amounts not paid when due shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the Late Payment Rate. In the event that any due date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such payment shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter. (c) As between Riverstart I, Riverstart II, and Riverstart III, and without limiting each such Co- Owners joint and several liability under Sections 6.9 and 6.10(a), within sixty (60) days after the end of each calendar year, Riverstart I, Riverstart II, and Riverstart III will review the Extraordinary Maintenance and O&M Costs for the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Extra High Voltage Equipment, the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Control House Equipment, and the Headwaters / Riverstart / Riverstart II / Riverstart III Substation Equipment. If such review reasonably demonstrates that one of the aforementioned Co-Owners is responsible for an increase in any incremental costs and/or liabilities associated with such Extraordinary Maintenance or O&M Costs, that entity shall refund or reimburse to the remaining of the aforementioned Co-Owners the share of these expenses that such remaining aforementioned Co-Owners previously paid to Operator in accordance with Section 6.9 and/or Section 6.10(a). For avoidance of doubt, Headwaters I shall not be entitled to any refund under this section. Any refund must be paid to the respective Co-Owners within ninety (90) days after the end of that calendar year; provided, that any refund amounts that are the subject of a bona fide dispute shall not be due and payable until [thirty (30)] days after the applicable dispute has been resolved. The refunds shall be delivered to Co-Owners as set forth in Section 17.15. Any amounts not refunded when due shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the Late Payment Rate. In the even that any due date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such refund shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter.
6.11 Disputes. 1. Consideration by the Authorized Representatives.
All questions concerning interpretation of this Agreement, the acceptable fulfillment of the Parties respective obligations hereunder, as well as all other questions regarding this Agreement in each case that cannot readily be resolved by the Parties shall be resolved in accordance with this Exhibit D. In the event that the authorized representatives of the Parties cannot reach agreement on any question arising under this Agreement, such dispute shall be referred to senior officers of the Parties pursuant to Paragraph 2 below.
2. Negotiations by Senior Officers.
Any disputes arising pursuant to this Agreement that cannot be resolved by the authorized representatives of the Parties within fourteen (14) days after receipt of notice of such dispute (specifically referencing this Exhibit D) shall be referred to the vice president or other senior officer of each of the Parties having executive responsibility for such Co-Owners Facility or the performance of the Operators responsibilities, as applicable. If such senior officers, negotiating in good faith, fail to reach an agreement within a reasonable period of time, not exceeding twenty (20) days after such referral, then any Party to such dispute may institute proceedings as set forth in Paragraph 3 below.
3. Formal Dispute Resolution.
(a) If a dispute described in Paragraph 2 is not resolved by the executive management of the Parties, the Parties shall engage in non-binding mediation of such dispute. Such mediation shall be conducted (i) in Houston, Texas, (ii) within thirty (30) days of a Party instituting dispute resolution under this Paragraph 3, (iii) by a single, impartial mediator who is selected by the mutual agreement of the Parties, and (iv) in accordance with such procedures as may be adopted by such mediator. Such mediation shall not, without the express agreement of the Parties at the time, extend for a period of more than two (2) days. Each Party may be represented by persons of such Partys choice during such mediation. Nothing herein shall be deemed to grant any mediator the authority to impose a resolution of any dispute being mediated. Any information introduced, proposals made or positions taken in the mediation shall be deemed to be confidential and for settlement purposes only and may not be introduced by another Party in any subsequent litigation of the matters subject to mediation. The Co- Owners shall share the costs of the mediator, including any fees and meeting room rentals.
(b) If a dispute described in Paragraph 2 is not resolved by the executive management of the Parties and the Parties have not otherwise resolved such dispute through mediation pursuant to Paragraph 3(a), a Party may submit the matter at issue for resolution in an action brought before the courts of the State of Indiana in the County of White or in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Indiana, which courts shall have nonexclusive jurisdiction with respect to such matters.
